ion that there is appropriate employment available for people who are expected to retire later. 'Gender, ageing and extended working life' challenges both this narrative, and the gender-neutral way the expectation for extending working lives is presented in most policy-making circles. The international contributors to this book - part of the Ageing in a Global Context series - apply life-course approaches to understanding evolving definitions of work and retirement. They consider the range of transitions from paid work to retirement that are potentially different for women and men in different family circumstances and occupational locations, and offer solutions governments should consider to enable them to evaluate existing policies. Based on evidence from Australia, Germany, Ireland, Portugal, Sweden, the United Kingdom and the United States, this is essential reading for researchers and students, and for policymakers who formulate and implement employment and pensions policy at national and international levels.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 27. Jan 2023) 0aLife span, Productive. 0aRetirement age. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Gerontology.2bisacsh1 aAlvinius, Aida, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrooke, Elizabeth, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCalasanti, Toni, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCasaca, Sara Falcão, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDuvvury, Nata, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEngström, Lars-Gunnar, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFinn, Caroline, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHokema, Anna, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKrekula, Clary